I am applying for the Lecturer position in the Department of Economics at Dartmouth College.
Currently, I am a PhD candidate in Economics at Southern Methodist University, specializing in Applied Microeconomics with an emphasis on Culture and Gender Economics, and I expect to complete my degree by May 2026.

My research explores how entertainment media both reflects and shapes economic behavior.
I develop novel methods using generative AI to extract cultural values from TV shows and test how these values affect individuals' behaviors and attitudes.

As an educator, I strive to make economics accessible and relevant for all students by emphasizing clarity and active learning. I translate complex theories into intuitive language, bridging technical concepts with everyday understanding, and support this with formal tools like formulas and graphs. I have experience teaching microeconomics and econometrics, and have also served as a teaching assistant for macroeconomics, making me well-prepared to teach any introductory economics courses. In my teaching, I prioritize hands-on engagement, using workshops and collaborative problem solving to reinforce concepts—creating a supportive environment where students feel comfortable participating and learning from mistakes. This approach has been well received, as reflected in strong student evaluations and positive feedback on my teaching style and classroom environment.

My approach aligns closely with Dartmouth's commitment to a community of teacher-scholars who advance undergraduate education. At Dartmouth, where fostering critical thinking and a collaborative spirit are central, my use of AI to analyze cultural influences in economic behavior complements the department's emphasis on innovative and interdisciplinary teaching approaches. Having mentored student athletes, I value personalized student engagement and am eager to contribute to the vibrant academic environment in Hanover through in-person instruction and mentoring. Additionally, my interdisciplinary research experience, recognized by the Dedman College Interdisciplinary Institute Fellowship, equips me to support Dartmouth's welcoming and diverse community while advancing economic scholarship that bridges theory and real-world culture.
